18/06/2007
ANKARA, Turkey -- The Constitutional Court will discuss the complaint filed by the opposition Republican People's Party (CHP) over the recent approval of constitutional reforms Tuesday (June 19th). 
The reforms include electing the president via popular vote, reducing the president's term from seven to five years, and reducing Parliament's term from five to four years. 
The ruling Justice and Development Party proposed the reforms, which Parliament has twice approved. 
Bu the CHP says constitutional and parliamentary rules were violated during the approval process. 
(Turkish Daily News, Zaman - 18/06/07)
